article.headline: Hodges, Augustus lead balanced LSU attack
article.linkText: Gunter still sick, but No. 16 LSU gets her 700th win
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Doneeka Hodges' big night helped her
coach have one of her own.

Hodges scored 22 points to lead LSU to a 92-65 victory over
Arkansas Thursday night as fans waved yellow signs with the number
700 on them.

The victory was the 700th for LSU coach Sue Gunter, although she
missed the game, still sidelined by bronchitis and a viral
infection.

"I think it's great for Coach Gunter and it says a lot about
the program we have here and about all of us that are fortunate
enough to be part of it," Hodges said.

It was also the 300th victory on their home court for the
16th-ranked Tigers (19-4, 7-2 Southeastern Conference).

The Razorbacks (14-8, 3-6) have dropped five of their last six.

Gunter, who missed her eighth game of the season, was at
practice Wednesday, watching from a chair courtside.

She wanted to be back for the landmark victory -- only
Tennessee's Pat Summitt (840) and Texas' Jody Conradt (838) have
more wins in women's basketball -- but said she would defer to her
doctors.

"We tried not to get pumped up about that," Seimone Augustus
said. "Coach wouldn't want us to do that, so we just wanted to
come out and win. I'm happy that Coach Gunter is at the top with
some of the best coaches like Pat Summit and Jodie Conradt of
Texas. She's a great coach and we love her."

Although Gunter wasn't at the game, she has still been busy with
the team this season, assistant coach Pokey Chatman said.

"Coach Gunter is only out one game night, so it's not that big
of a deal," Chatman said. "She's at practice, she's at film,
she's in the office. She's calling in and she's writing notes,
she's fussing and doing all the things we have to do to get them
playing. On game nights, that's the night any one of us could be
missing because the kids are so focused and all the preparation has
been done."

Gunter's record does not include the first six years of her
career. Those records have never been approved by the NCAA.

Both teams had five players in double figures.

Augustus scored 20 points for LSU, Temeka Johnson had 14 points
and 15 assists, Wendlyn Jones added 13 and Hanna Biernacka had 12.

Kristin Moore and April Seggebruch each had 13 points to lead
Arkansas. Rochelle Vaughn had 12 and Shameka Christon, who was
averaging 21.3 points a game, scored 10.

"They were really pressing," Christon said. "I don't know how
to describe it, but it was definitely good defense."

LSU opened the second half with an 8-2 run that put them up
44-34 on Biernaka's fast-break layup with 17:36 left and never
looked back. The Tigers led by as much as 29 and never less than
seven the rest of the game.

"It got embarrassing at the end," said Arkansas coach Susie
Gardner. "But a turnover here, a missed shot there ..."

Gardner pointed out that Arkansas was only down by seven points
with 6:47 remaining.

LSU out-rebounded the Razorbacks 36-27 and out-shot them 60
percent to 40 percent from the field. Arkansas made only 6 of 18
3-point attempts and just 13 of 19 free throws.

After a close first half, LSU went up 21-20 on Hodges' jumper
with 7:07 left. The Tigers stretched the lead to seven points, only
to see Arkansas come back to within two points at 32-30 on free
throws by Katrina Nesby with 34 seconds remaining.

LSU held on for a 36-32 lead at the break.
